<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Hesperocyparis</i> <i>forbesii</i> or <i>Hesperocyparis</i> <i>nevadensis</i> is dominant in the tree canopy with <i>Juniperus</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>monophylla</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>sabiniana</i> or <i>Quercus</i> <i>douglasii</i> and emergent above a shrub canopy with <i>Adenostoma</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>glandulosa</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>glauca</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>otayensis</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>crassifolius</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>cuneatus</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> ×<i>otayensis</i>, <i>Chamaebatia</i> <i>australis</i>, <i>Dendromecon</i> <i>rigida</i>, <i>Helianthemum</i> <i>scoparium</i>, <i>Malosma</i> <i>laurina</i>, <i>Pickeringia</i> <i>montana</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>berberidifolia</i>, <i>Salvia</i> <i>munzii</i> or <i>Xylococcus</i> <i>bicolor</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text"> Trees < 15 m; canopy is open to intermittent. Shrub layer is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse to intermittent. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Hesperocyparis forbesii</i> > 50% relative cover in the tree layer and/or emergent over a layer of chapparal  (AECOM 2013, Sproul et al. 2013).</li>
		
		<li><i>Hesperocyparis nevadensis</i> > 30% relative cover in the tree canopy (Ratchford et al. 2022a).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Dry, exposed hillsides and ridgetops, stream banks, and arroyos. Soils are deep or shallow over alkaline clay, sandstone, granitic, metamorphic, mafic, and ultramafic substrates.  </div>
</div>

        
