<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Hesperocyparis forbesii </i>is a fire-maintained, closed-cone conifer with multiple trunks and shrubby growth that attains a height to 10 m. On sites with high density after fire, plants can be dwarfed and only reach 1-2 m at maturity (Stottlemyer and Lathrop 1981). Trees usually grow vigorously for 90 years; the oldest known tree is more than 200 years old (Keeley and Davis 2007, Vogl et al. 1977). Seedlings are shade intolerant and establish best on bare mineral soil. Foliage is lost when growing in shade. Chaparral plants inhibit the establishment of <i>H. forbesii, </i>but most chaparral species cannot compete on infertile soils where the trees grow (Armstrong 1978, Barbour 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Hesperocyparis nevadensis </i>is a small-sized conifer that grows to a height of 15 m. Cone production is abundant on mature trees. Cones remain closed and persist on trees until opened by heat, desiccation, or age. Seeds shed gradually over several months after cones open. Seed germination and seedling establishment are best on bare mineral soil. Seedlings are sensitive to excessive moisture (Barbour 2007, Sullivan 1993b). <i>H. nevadensis </i>is the most xerophytic of the California cypresses. Average annual precipitation of the known stands is about 22.9 cm/year. Unlike other cypresses in the state, <i>H. nevadensis </i>appears to have a relatively wide tolerance for a variety of soil types.The genus <i>Cupressus </i>is restricted to the Old World; cypresses in California belong to the genus <i>Hesperocyparis </i>(Bartel et al. 2003, Little 2006, Adams et al. 2009, Terry et al. 2012). <br/>
<br/>
Stands of <i>Hesperocyparis forbesii </i> exist in the Santa Ana Mountains, on Sierra Peak and in Gypsum Canyon in Orange Co., and in the California portion of the Peninsular Ranges on Guatay Mountain, Otay Mountain, and Tecata Peak in San Diego Co. It is considered a CNPS list 1B.1 plant in California. Stands are numerous in Baja California in the Sierra Bola north of Valle Guadalupe, in the hills near La Puerta, in the mountains east of the bay of Ensenada, in the coastal bluffs west of San Vicente, and locally in the coastal foothills west of the Sierra San Pedro Martir (Minnich 1987, Minnich and Franco-Vizcaino 1998).<br/>
<br/>
Stands of <i>Hesperocyparis nevadensis </i>occur on heavy black clay, ultrafine red clay, and decomposed or fractured granite (Twisselmann 1967). More than ten stands occur in the southern Sierra Nevada in Kern Co. Bartel (1980) described nine; Shevock (pers. comm. 2006) discovered three more recently. The largest is in the Bodfish Grove Botanical Area on the Sequoia National Forest. Stands typically occur in relatively mesic situations within a matrix of chaparral types. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
