<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Hesperocyparis nevadensis </i> and <i>H. forbesii </i> are fire-adapted species with serotinous cones. Although low-intensity surface fires are lethal to most trees, their resinous foliage, thin bark, and mixed chaparral habitat ensure that fires ladder into the canopy and open the cones with extreme heat. Seeds fall from cones in the first few months following fire and germinate on bare mineral soil or in washes after water dispersal often creating even aged thickets (Sullivan 1993b). Peak cone reproduction and timing for fire is at age 40-50 years. Other estimates for fire include return intervals from 15 to 63 years in the last century, as compared to more natural fire return intervals from 50 to 100 years (Esser 1994c).
For <i>Hesperocyparis nevadensis, </i> the Bodfish stand appears to have a varied fire history with both young and old trees. Some, such as the Back Canyon stand, are relatively old (over 100 years). Other smaller stands are even aged: examples include Hobo Ridge (fire 1966) and Stormy Canyon (fire 1924). Long Canyon RNA (Cheng 2004) has had two separate fires (ca. 1950, 1984), the more recent only burning one of the stands. Cypress seedlings at the 1984 burn had densities of 700-7300/ha and ranged from 8 to 46 cm tall in 1989 (Keeler-Wolf 1990b).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
