    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ep, Es, Eu). Bartel (1980) described the distribution and ecology of <i>Hesperocyparis nevadensis </i>stands, and reports on the basal area, density, and frequency for woody species for two of the larger stands. Keeler- Wolf (1990b) reported on these stand attributes for two stands in the Long Canyon RNA (Cheng 2004). They were within a matrix with chaparral containing <i>Arctostaphylos glauca, Ceanothus greggii,</i> and <i>Fremontodendron californicum</i> prior to the 1984 fire. These stands occur primarily on dark metamorphics; the adjacent stands on granitics lack the cypress.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fd). Stands of <i>Hesperocyparis nevadensis </i>have been surveyed and mapped in the southern Sierra Nevada Foothills near Lake Isabella (Ratchford et al. 2021a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bg, Bi). Stands of <i>Hesperocyparis forbesii </i>are expected in the Verdugo Mountains based on collections found in the Consortium of California Herbaria (2018), Los Angeles County. Stands have also been surveyed and mapped in the southeastern edge of 261Bi near the Otay Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bb, Bf, Bn-o). Minnich and Everett (2001) described  <i>Hesperocyparis forbesii </i>stands in the section in the Peninsular Ranges. Astand has been observed near Warm Springs Mountain.CVIS (2007) included a stand sampled on Otay Mountain, and Zedler (1981) reported tree age and stand density at Otay Mountain and Tecate Peak. Barbour (2007) noted species cover and density of perennial plants in recently burned and older stands on Sierra Ana Mountains. Those in the Guatay Mountain RNA (Cheng 2004) occur on gabbro substrates.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> California’s stands are threatened by residential development and other demands from growing near urban areas. Zedler (1977) suggested that frequent human-caused fires are causing declines in <i>Hesperocyparis forbesii </i>populations on Tecate Peak and Otay Mountain. Many of the known locations of these species have been impacted by fire in the last 20 years.

Properly timed fire return intervals are important for maintaing stands. Fire return intervals should be long enough to allow a cone crop to develop, but short enough to maintain a viable seed bank in the trees. Today’s fire return intervals are shorter than historical ones (Zedler 1995), and shorter fire return intervals do not allow plants to mature and build up adequate seed reserves, leading to local population extirpation (Keeley and Davis 2007). However, it only takes one recruit to replace a mature tree, so local studies may be insufficient to evaluate a species status. A better approach would be to consider the spatial turnover of mature stands from repeat aerial photography (R. A. Minnich, pers. comm. 2007). Also, for a preservation strategy, it may be better to consider ways to maintain the maximum number of mature stands rather than trying to alter fire return intervals. </div>
</div>

    

    

